{"descriptions":[{"id":331,"title":null,"content":"\u003cp\u003eLiterally “link-sound,” designates the complement of the noun, and is translated by “of”; it may also correspond to the conjunction “but” (L).\u003c/p\u003e","source_url":null,"is_primary":false,"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:31 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:31 UTC","authors":[{"id":"2","fullname":"David Germano"}]},{"id":332,"title":null,"content":"\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eTraditional grammars refer to this marker as \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eའབྲེལ་སྒྲ་\u003c/span\u003e, literally \u0026ldquo;link sound,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;relation sound,\u0026rdquo; and it is commonly translated by the English \u0026ldquo;of.\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eThe genitive has several variant forms depending on the final letter of the preceding word. These variants are: \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eགི་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eགྱི་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཀྱི་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eའི་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eའི་\u003c/span\u003e is used after a vowel and \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eའ་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eགི་\u003c/span\u003e is used after \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eག་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eང་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཀྱི་\u003c/span\u003e is used after \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eད་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབ་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eས་\u003c/span\u003e, and the \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eད་དྲག་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eགྱི་\u003c/span\u003e is used after \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eན་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eམ་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eར་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eལ་\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eIn Classical Tibetan, vowels and the letter \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eའ་\u003c/span\u003e may be followed by the variant \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཡི་\u003c/span\u003e; this is especially true in poetry, to suit the requirements of the meter.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eThe genitive is used not only to form noun complements, possessive pronouns, and adjectives, but also relative clauses. In this case, it may be translated by a relative pronoun such as \u0026ldquo;that,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;who,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;where,\u0026rdquo; etc. The complement that is marked by the genitive always precedes the noun to which it refers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eངའི་གྲོགས་པོ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;My friend\u0026rdquo; (Literally: \u0026ldquo;The friend of me\u0026rdquo;) \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཁོང་གི་ཕྱག་སྨྱུག་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;His pen\u0026rdquo; (Literally: \u0026ldquo;The pen of him\u0026rdquo;) \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབཀྲ་ཤིས་ལགས་ཀྱི་བུ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Trashi\u0026rsquo;s son\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eབླ་མའི་སླློབ་མ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;The lama\u0026rsquo;s disciple\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eགཞུང་གི་ལས་བྱེད་པ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Government civil servant\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eདགེ་རྒན་གྱི་དེབ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;The teacher\u0026rsquo;s book\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eདེབ་ནང་ལ་ཡོད་པའི་པར་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;The photo that\u0026rsquo;s in the book\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eIn the literary language the genitive case may also correspond to the conjunction \u0026ldquo;but.\u0026rdquo;\u003c/p\u003e","source_url":null,"is_primary":true,"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:31 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:31 UTC","authors":[{"id":"6","fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre"}]}]}